{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7aca4ed0-9510-4e8b-bee4-097be0db1d89","content":"Here's my analysis of the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deep Nested Import Chain\n\nThe project imports `level1.props`, which imports `level2.props`, which imports `level3.props`. Each nested import adds overhead during the **evaluation phase** — MSBuild must locate, open, parse, and evaluate each file before it can proceed. Deep chains multiply this cost, especially in large solutions where the project graph is evaluated repeatedly.\n\n## 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern\n\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n\nThe `**\\*.*` glob scans the **entire directory tree** during evaluation. It will crawl into `.git/`, `node_modules/`, and any other large directories that aren't explicitly excluded. This is extremely expensive on disk I/O. Fix: restrict to specific subdirectories or file extensions, and leverage `DefaultItemExcludes` to exclude common noise folders.\n\n## 3. File I/O via Property Function During Evaluation\n\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n\nThis calls `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` during the **evaluation phase** — the phase where MSBuild resolves properties, items, and imports. File I/O here blocks evaluation and cannot be parallelized or cached by MSBuild. Unlike targets (which run during the **execution phase** and can be incremental/skipped), property functions execute unconditionally every time the project is evaluated.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| Deep imports | Flatten or consolidate into a single `.props` file |\n| Broad glob | Use targeted patterns like `src\\**\\*.cs` and add `.git;node_modules` to excludes |\n| File I/O in property | Move to a target that reads the file during execution, or use a `ReadLinesFromFile` task |\n\nThe key distinction: **evaluation** happens for every build invocation (and IDE project load) and should be as cheap as possible. **Execution** is where expensive I/O and computation belong.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"390ec639-2903-4a6d-97b2-752c619358f3","outputTokens":512,"requestId":"7C17:149BD4:C0367D:DC1A1E:6A027FC1"},"id":"f06546d0-0bd9-4892-b1f2-4d6981a557ee","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:18:07.436Z","parentId":"88717a2c-2c2e-4298-8594-41fcde7326b6"}
